1
00:00:01,010 --> 00:00:06,850
Bad data visualizations can be summed up as visuals that don't convey your message well.

2
00:00:06,850 --> 00:00:11,475
If a visualization is misleading or hides and distracts your message,

3
00:00:11,475 --> 00:00:14,580
you need to consider changes to your visualization.

4
00:00:14,580 --> 00:00:17,280
Let's look at some misleading examples.

5
00:00:17,280 --> 00:00:21,420
This is a popular image for showing bad visualizations.

6
00:00:21,420 --> 00:00:25,220
Here, you can see that this plot is misleading by making

7
00:00:25,220 --> 00:00:31,090
a small difference seem much larger than it actually is by zooming in on the difference.

8
00:00:31,090 --> 00:00:35,505
This is a poor visualization due to the fact that it's misleading.

9
00:00:35,505 --> 00:00:38,750
A second example was made popular by Cole.

10
00:00:38,750 --> 00:00:42,110
Consider these two pie charts for understanding how

11
00:00:42,110 --> 00:00:47,170
a summer science camp for kids impacts their interests on learning about science.

12
00:00:47,170 --> 00:00:52,060
Can you tell if the camp was effective in raising the interest rates in science?

13
00:00:52,060 --> 00:00:57,075
This is an example of a visual that hides or distracts from the message.

14
00:00:57,075 --> 00:01:00,020
Comparing the areas of the pie charts and

15
00:01:00,020 --> 00:01:03,640
all the colors make it difficult to see the message.

16
00:01:03,640 --> 00:01:07,220
Another plot from Cole's book is this pie chart.

17
00:01:07,220 --> 00:01:12,650
You might guess that this piece of the pie is the largest in terms of the suppliers.

18
00:01:12,650 --> 00:01:15,800
You would be wrong, it's actually this piece.

19
00:01:15,800 --> 00:01:18,840
The 3D aspect of the chart is misleading.

20
00:01:18,840 --> 00:01:25,085
Again, humans are not great at identifying differences based on these areas.

21
00:01:25,085 --> 00:01:29,270
Here is an example of a racetrack chart.

22
00:01:29,270 --> 00:01:32,720
Though one bar is clearly longer than the other,

23
00:01:32,720 --> 00:01:34,895
they represent the same percentage.

24
00:01:34,895 --> 00:01:37,010
This makes for some confusion.

25
00:01:37,010 --> 00:01:39,665
Additionally, the bright red here,

26
00:01:39,665 --> 00:01:42,175
suggests that this group is more important.

27
00:01:42,175 --> 00:01:43,910
If this isn't the case,

28
00:01:43,910 --> 00:01:45,935
then this coloring seems misleading.

29
00:01:45,935 --> 00:01:47,645
With just two bars,

30
00:01:47,645 --> 00:01:49,580
we might not even need a chart,

31
00:01:49,580 --> 00:01:52,325
but rather just a statement of the message.

32
00:01:52,325 --> 00:01:55,100
Visualizations become more useful as

33
00:01:55,100 --> 00:01:58,235
the amount of information we need to convey increases.

34
00:01:58,235 --> 00:01:59,675
At the same time,

35
00:01:59,675 --> 00:02:02,240
adding extra elements to the visuals that do

36
00:02:02,240 --> 00:02:05,075
not convey the message in your data should be avoided.

37
00:02:05,075 --> 00:02:09,430
I urge you to strive for elegance and simplicity in your visuals.

38
00:02:09,430 --> 00:02:13,070
Here, you saw some examples of poor visuals.

39
00:02:13,070 --> 00:02:16,520
You might have some ideas of how to improve these already.

40
00:02:16,520 --> 00:02:21,150
We will look at some improved visuals in the upcoming concepts.

